{
  "response": "# Disclosure / Accordion Widget Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users (NVDA on Windows, VoiceOver on macOS), keyboard-only users, low-vision users, touch users (mobile)\n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA (Windows), VoiceOver (macOS), keyboard-only\n\n**Feature:** A reusable React disclosure/accordion widget where each item has a button that shows/hides an associated content panel, with multiple panels openable simultaneously (non-exclusive).\n**Risk Level:** Low\n**Component Type:** Disclosure (set of independent disclosures)\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n1. **What is being built?** A reusable disclosure component: a list of items, each with a trigger button that toggles the visibility of its own content panel. Multiple panels may be open at once.\n2. **User need:** Lets users scan a list of section headings (e.g., FAQ questions) and expand only the content they care about, reducing cognitive load and scroll length.\n3. **Who needs accessibility?** Everyone. Specifically: screen reader users need the expanded/collapsed state announced; keyboard-only users need to reach and toggle each item without a mouse; low-vision users need a visible focus indicator and a non-color state cue; touch users need targets large enough to tap reliably.\n4. **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA.\n5. **Assistive technologies:** NVDA (Windows, with Firefox/Chrome), VoiceOver (macOS, with Safari), keyboard-only operation. Touch on mobile (iOS VoiceOver / Android TalkBack benefit from the same semantics).\n6. **Risk level:** **Low.** This is a well-documented APG pattern with simple interactions, no focus trap, no roving tabindex, no live region. The risk is in the details (correct ARIA wiring, state announced, non-color cue, focus visibility), not in the architecture.\n7. **Existing code:** None \u2014 new component.\n8. **Constraints:** Must live in a design system (reusable, tokenized, no hardcoded one-off styling). Must support mobile/touch (target size, no hover-only affordances).\n\n**Pattern decision \u2014 Disclosure, NOT the ARIA Accordion pattern.** Because multiple panels open independently and there is no single-selection / \"only one open\" behavior, this is a **set of independent Disclosure widgets**, not the APG Accordion pattern. The Accordion pattern adds composite keyboard navigation (Up/Down/Home/End arrow keys to move between headers, optional roving focus). The Disclosure pattern does not \u2014 each button is just a normal Tab stop. Choosing Disclosure here avoids implementing arrow-key navigation users won't expect for independent toggles, and keeps the component simpler and lighter. (See APG: a disclosure is \"a button that controls visibility of a section of content\"; the accordion is a set of headers where typically only one section is shown at a time.)\n\n- APG Disclosure pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/\n- APG Disclosure example (FAQ): https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/examples/disclosure-faq/\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\n**Landmarks:** This is a component, not a page, so it does not own landmarks. It is dropped into an existing `<main>` or `<section>`. The component must NOT introduce its own `<main>`/`<nav>`. If the disclosure set is a discrete page region (e.g., an FAQ block), the consuming page may wrap it in a `<section aria-labelledby=\"...\">` with its own heading \u2014 that is the page's responsibility, documented here so the integrator knows the component does not do it.\n\n**Heading hierarchy (WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels):**\n- Each disclosure trigger button is wrapped in a heading element so screen-reader users can navigate item-to-item with heading shortcuts (H key in NVDA, rotor in VoiceOver) and so the document outline reflects the section structure.\n- The component must accept a **configurable heading level** prop (e.g., `headingLevel={3}`) rather than hardcoding `<h3>`. The correct level depends on where the component sits in the host page's outline; hardcoding guarantees a heading-skip violation somewhere. Default to a sensible level (e.g., 3) and document that the integrator must set it to fit the surrounding outline (no skipped levels).\n- The button is the **only** content of the heading. The heading wraps the button; the button is the interactive element. Do not put the visible label text outside the button \u2014 the button must contain the label so its accessible name is the section title.\n\n**List structure (WCAG 1.3.1):** The set of items is a true list. Wrap items in a `<ul>` with one `<li>` per disclosure item, so screen readers announce \"list, N items\" and item position. (Headings inside list items are valid and give users two complementary navigation modes \u2014 by list and by heading.)\n\n**Element choices:**\n| Region | Element | Why | WCAG |\n|--------|---------|-----|------|\n| Item set | `<ul>` \u2192 `<li>` | True list; announces count and position | 1.3.1 |\n| Trigger wrapper | `<h3>` (configurable level) | Heading navigation + document outline | 1.3.1, 2.4.6 |\n| Trigger | native `<button type=\"button\">` | Gets keyboard, focus, Enter/Space, and `button` role for free; avoids re-implementing button semantics on a `<div>` | 4.1.2, 2.1.1 |\n| Panel | `<div>` or `<section>`, with `id`, controlled by `hidden` | Container toggled by the button | 1.3.1 |\n\n`type=\"button\"` is required so that, if the widget is ever rendered inside a `<form>`, the trigger does not submit the form. (WCAG 3.2.2 On Input \u2014 prevents an unexpected context change on activation.)\n\n**HTML structure stub (structure + ARIA only \u2014 not implementation code):**\n\n```\n<ul class=\"disclosure-set\">\n  <li class=\"disclosure-item\">\n    <h3 class=\"disclosure-heading\">            <!-- level is configurable -->\n      <button type=\"button\"\n              id=\"disc-trigger-1\"\n              aria-expanded=\"false\"            <!-- becomes \"true\" when open -->\n              aria-controls=\"disc-panel-1\">\n        <span class=\"disclosure-label\">Question or section title</span>\n        <span class=\"disclosure-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><!-- chevron --></span>\n      </button>\n    </h3>\n    <div id=\"disc-panel-1\"\n         role=\"region\"                          <!-- optional; see note below -->\n         aria-labelledby=\"disc-trigger-1\"       <!-- only if role=\"region\" used -->\n         hidden>                                <!-- present when collapsed, removed when open -->\n      Panel content\u2026\n    </div>\n  </li>\n  <!-- repeat <li> per item; ids must be unique per item -->\n</ul>\n```\n\n**Note on `role=\"region\"` for the panel:** The APG FAQ example wraps each panel in a `role=\"region\"` labelled by its trigger, so the panel becomes a navigable landmark. This is helpful when panels contain substantial content (multiple paragraphs, forms). **However**, do not add `role=\"region\"` to many short panels \u2014 a dozen regions clutters the landmark list and becomes noise. **Decision rule:** apply `role=\"region\" aria-labelledby=\"<triggerId>\"` only when panels hold rich/long content; omit it for short FAQ answers. Make it a prop (`landmarkPanels` boolean) so the design system can choose per use. If `role=\"region\"` is omitted, also omit `aria-labelledby` on the panel (a labelled non-landmark `<div>` adds nothing).\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n**APG pattern:** Disclosure \u2014 https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/\n\nEach trigger is an independent disclosure button. Because we use a **native `<button>`**, the role, focusability, and Enter/Space activation come from the platform; we only add the expanded/collapsed state and the controls relationship.\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|--------|-------------|----------|------|------|\n| Disclosure trigger (one per item) | [Disclosure](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/) | **Tab** moves focus to the button; **Shift+Tab** moves backward. **Enter** toggles the panel. **Space** toggles the panel. | `aria-expanded` (true/false), `aria-controls` (panel id) | 2.1.1 Keyboard; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value; 1.3.1 Info and Relationships |\n\n**Keyboard interaction model (per APG Disclosure):**\n- **Tab / Shift+Tab:** Move focus to / from the trigger button. Each trigger is an ordinary stop in the tab sequence \u2014 no roving tabindex, no arrow-key navigation between items (that belongs to the Accordion pattern, which we deliberately did not adopt).\n- **Enter:** Toggles `aria-expanded` and shows/hides the panel. (Native button gives this for free.)\n- **Space:** Same as Enter. (Native button gives this for free.)\n- **No Escape behavior** is required \u2014 a disclosure is not an overlay; collapsing is done by re-activating the trigger.\n\n**Do not suppress native behavior.** Because a native `<button>` is used, do not add `keydown` handlers that call `preventDefault()` on Space (which would break native activation) and do not add `role=\"button\"` (redundant) or `tabindex=\"0\"` (the button is already focusable). The only JS needed is the click/activate handler that flips state.\n\n**Screen reader experience:**\n- **On focus (collapsed):** \"Question or section title, collapsed, button\" (NVDA) / \"Question or section title, collapsed, button\" (VoiceOver). The order/wording varies by AT, but name + state + role are all conveyed because of the accessible name, `aria-expanded=\"false\"`, and the `button` role.\n- **On focus (expanded):** \"\u2026, expanded, button.\"\n- **On activation:** The AT announces the new state (\"expanded\" / \"collapsed\") because `aria-expanded` changed on the focused element. No live region is needed \u2014 the state lives on the control the user just operated, so the change is announced as part of the control. (This is exactly why the disclosure pattern does **not** need `aria-live`.)\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\nThis component needs **simple, explicit** focus management \u2014 no focus trap, no focus restoration, no roving tabindex. Spelling it out anyway, because \"even trivial components need focus management.\"\n\n1. **Tab order (WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order):** Source/DOM order = visual order = top-to-bottom: trigger 1, (if open) panel 1's focusable content, trigger 2, (if open) panel 2's content, \u2026 Do not reorder visually with CSS such that DOM order diverges from reading order.\n2. **Focus stays put on toggle (WCAG 2.4.3):** When the user activates a trigger, **focus remains on the trigger**. Do NOT move focus into the panel on expand and do NOT move focus elsewhere on collapse. Moving focus would be unexpected for a disclosure and could strand the user. The newly revealed content appears immediately after the trigger in the tab order, so the user reaches it with the next Tab if they want it.\n3. **Collapsed panel content is removed from the tab order:** Use the HTML `hidden` attribute (or `display:none`) on collapsed panels. This is essential: `hidden`/`display:none` removes the panel and any focusable elements inside it (links, form fields) from the tab order and from the accessibility tree. **Do not** hide panels with `visibility:hidden` + something focusable, and **do not** rely on `aria-hidden=\"true\"` alone \u2014 `aria-hidden` hides from AT but does NOT remove elements from keyboard tab order, so a keyboard user could Tab into an invisible collapsed panel (a keyboard trap-adjacent bug). In React, conditionally rendering the panel (not rendering it at all when collapsed) is also acceptable and equivalent for focus purposes; if you keep it mounted for animation, toggle `hidden`.\n4. **Focus indicator (WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible; 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum), new in 2.2):** Every trigger must show a clearly visible focus indicator when focused via keyboard. Use a **two-part indicator** \u2014 a solid `outline` plus a contrasting `box-shadow` ring \u2014 so it stays visible against any background the design system places it on. Use `:focus-visible` (not `:focus`) so the ring shows for keyboard/AT focus but not on mouse click. Ensure no sticky header or surrounding element overlaps the focused trigger such that the focus ring is hidden (2.4.11).\n5. **No skip link inside the component.** Skip links are a page-level concern (WCAG 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks); a single disclosure set is not a \"block\" to bypass. If the set is very long, the consuming page may add a \"skip past FAQ\" link \u2014 documented as the page's responsibility, out of scope for the component.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nThere are two real states per item: **collapsed** and **expanded**. Both must be conveyed visually AND programmatically.\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual indicator | Programmatic indicator | ARIA | WCAG |\n|-------|------------------|------------------------|------|------|\n| Collapsed | Chevron points right/down-closed; panel not shown; label text present | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` on the trigger; panel has `hidden` | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` | 1.4.1 Use of Color; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value |\n| Expanded | Chevron rotated (e.g., points up/open); panel shown below the trigger | `aria-expanded=\"true\"` on the trigger; `hidden` removed from panel | `aria-expanded=\"true\"` | 1.4.1; 4.1.2 |\n| Focused (keyboard) | Visible focus ring (outline + box-shadow) | Native focus | \u2014 | 2.4.7 Focus Visible |\n| Hover / active (mouse) | Subtle background change (enhancement only) | \u2014 | \u2014 | \u2014 |\n\n**Programmatic state details:**\n- `aria-expanded` on the trigger button is the single source of truth for state, toggled `true`/`false` on every activation. **WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value** \u2014 the state of the control must be programmatically determinable.\n- `aria-controls=\"<panelId>\"` on the trigger associates the button with the panel it shows/hides. **WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.** (Support note: `aria-controls` is inconsistently surfaced by screen readers, but it is part of the APG Disclosure pattern, costs nothing, and is correct; keep it. The state announcement does not depend on it.)\n- The panel's visibility (`hidden` present/absent) must always stay in sync with `aria-expanded`. A mismatch (e.g., `aria-expanded=\"true\"` but panel still `hidden`) is a defect \u2014 wire both from one state value.\n\n**The chevron/icon is decorative and MUST be hidden from AT.** The state is already conveyed by `aria-expanded`; the icon is a redundant visual cue. Mark it `aria-hidden=\"true\"` (or render it via CSS background / pseudo-element). If you use a text glyph such as `+` / `\u2212` or `\u25b8` / `\u25be`, wrap it in `<span aria-hidden=\"true\">` so screen readers don't announce \"plus\", \"minus\", or \"black right-pointing small triangle\" alongside the real \"expanded/collapsed\". **WCAG 4.1.2** (avoid redundant/confusing announcements); **WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content** (decorative content is hidden).\n\n**No live region.** Because state changes on the focused control and the AT announces the control's new state automatically, adding `aria-live` would cause double announcements. Do not add `role=\"status\"` / `aria-live` to this widget.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n1. **Color contrast (WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum):**\n   - Trigger label text vs. its background: \u2265 **4.5:1** (normal text) or \u2265 **3:1** if the label renders at large-text size (\u2265 24px, or \u2265 18.66px bold).\n   - Chevron icon and any border/divider used to convey structure: \u2265 **3:1** as a non-text UI component (WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast).\n   - Focus indicator: \u2265 **3:1** contrast against the adjacent background AND against the component's resting state (WCAG 1.4.11). The two-part (outline + box-shadow) technique guarantees this on light and dark surfaces.\n2. **Color is never the sole state cue (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color):** Expanded vs. collapsed must NOT be signaled by color alone. It is signaled by (a) the panel being visible or not \u2014 a layout/position change, and (b) the chevron orientation \u2014 a shape change, and (c) programmatically by `aria-expanded`. List of color-coded cues and their non-color alternative: *expanded state* \u2192 panel visible + chevron rotated (position + shape, not just color). No required-field/error coloring exists in this component.\n3. **Font sizing (WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text; 1.4.10 Reflow):** Use relative units (`rem`/`em`) for label text and paddings \u2014 design-system tokens, not hardcoded `px`. Layout must survive **200% zoom** and **400% zoom / 320 CSS px width** with no loss of content or horizontal scrolling \u2014 the trigger label wraps rather than truncates; the chevron stays beside the label.\n4. **Text spacing (WCAG 1.4.12 Text Spacing):** Content must not clip when users override line-height to 1.5\u00d7, letter-spacing 0.12em, word-spacing 0.16em, paragraph spacing 2\u00d7. Avoid fixed-height triggers that would clip a wrapped two-line label.\n5. **Touch target size (WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum), AA in 2.2):** Each trigger button's hit area must be at least **24\u00d724 CSS px** (the 2.2 AA minimum). **Recommended: 44\u00d744 CSS px** for comfortable mobile use. Make the **entire trigger row** the clickable button (full-width), not just the text or icon, so the tap target is generous and there is no tiny icon-only hit area. Ensure adjacent triggers have enough spacing/offset to meet the 24px und/spacing exception.\n6. **Reduced motion (WCAG 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions):** If the panel expand/collapse or chevron rotation is animated, wrap the animation in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` and disable it (instant show/hide) for users who request reduced motion. Animation must never be the only signal that state changed \u2014 the end state (panel shown/hidden) is what matters.\n7. **Dark mode / forced colors:** Source colors from design-system tokens so contrast holds in both light and dark themes (WCAG 1.4.3 in both). In Windows High Contrast / `forced-colors` mode, do not rely on a CSS background image for the chevron alone (background images can disappear) \u2014 ensure the state is still conveyed by `aria-expanded` + panel visibility, which forced-colors mode preserves.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n1. **Accessible name of each trigger (WCAG 2.4.4 Link Purpose / equivalently meaningful button name; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value):** The button's accessible name = its visible label text (the section title/question). Because the label is real text inside the button, the visible label and the accessible name match (WCAG 2.5.3 Label in Name is satisfied by construction). **Do not** use `aria-label` to rename the button \u2014 that would risk diverging from the visible text and break voice-control users who say the visible words. **Do not** use `title` as the accessible name \u2014 `title` only produces a tooltip and is not a reliable accessible name across screen readers.\n2. **Icon (WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content):** Decorative chevron \u2192 `aria-hidden=\"true\"` (or CSS-rendered). It carries no information the label and `aria-expanded` don't already carry.\n3. **Panel content:** Authored content inside panels follows normal content a11y rules \u2014 meaningful link text (WCAG 2.4.4, no bare \"click here\"), `alt` text on any images (WCAG 1.1.1), correct heading levels *within* the panel that continue below the trigger's heading level (e.g., trigger is `<h3>`, sub-headings inside the panel are `<h4>`), and meaningful reading order (WCAG 1.3.2). These are the content author's responsibility; document them so authors don't break the outline.\n4. **Language (WCAG 3.1.1 / 3.1.2):** Handled at the page/`<html lang>` level; the component inherits it. If a label or panel contains a phrase in another language, wrap that phrase in `<span lang=\"\u2026\">`.\n5. **No instructions needed:** The control is self-describing (a button whose name is the section title, with announced expanded/collapsed state). No extra \"click to expand\" helper text is required, and adding it would be redundant for AT users who already hear \"collapsed, button.\"\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n**Run every test against BOTH states (collapsed and expanded) and against a multi-item instance** (to catch duplicate-`id` bugs).\n\n1. **Automated (axe-core via the a11y-test / accessibility-testing path):**\n   - Validates: no duplicate `id`s across triggers/panels; `aria-controls` references an element that exists; valid ARIA attribute/value usage; button has an accessible name; heading order; color-contrast of the label text.\n   - Run on the collapsed render AND the expanded render.\n   - **Known blind spots axe will NOT catch:** whether the *state change* is announced, whether focus stays on the trigger, whether Space/Enter actually toggle, whether the chevron is correctly hidden. Those need the manual checks below.\n2. **Keyboard testing (a11y-test, real key events \u2014 Playwright `page.keyboard.press` / agent-browser CDP, never synthetic events):**\n   - **Tab** reaches each trigger in DOM/visual order; **Shift+Tab** reverses.\n   - **Enter** toggles the panel; `aria-expanded` flips `false`\u2194`true`; panel `hidden` is added/removed in sync.\n   - **Space** toggles the panel identically (and does not scroll the page instead of activating).\n   - When a panel is **collapsed**, Tab does NOT land on anything inside it (focus skips the hidden content).\n   - When a panel is **expanded**, Tab moves from the trigger into the panel's focusable content next.\n   - Focus indicator is clearly visible on every trigger at 100%, 200%, and 400% zoom, and is not obscured by any sticky element (2.4.11).\n   - Toggling does not move focus off the trigger.\n3. **Screen reader testing (real AT \u2014 required, automation cannot substitute):**\n   - **NVDA + Firefox/Chrome (Windows):** Focus a trigger \u2192 hears name + \"collapsed\" + \"button\". Activate \u2192 hears \"expanded\". Activate again \u2192 hears \"collapsed\". Navigate by heading (H) \u2192 lands on each trigger. Navigate by list \u2192 hears \"list, N items\" and item position.\n   - **VoiceOver + Safari (macOS):** Same expectations via VO rotor (headings, form controls). Confirm the chevron glyph is NOT announced.\n   - Confirm no double announcement of state (would indicate an erroneous live region).\n4. **Visual / responsive regression:**\n   - 200% zoom and 400% zoom (320px width): label wraps, no horizontal scroll, no clipped text, chevron stays placed.\n   - `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`: expand/collapse and chevron rotation are instant.\n   - `forced-colors: active` (Windows High Contrast): trigger, label, focus ring, and expanded/collapsed distinction remain perceivable.\n   - Touch target \u2265 24\u00d724 CSS px (target 44\u00d744) verified on a mobile viewport.\n5. **DOM verification (required \u2014 not satisfied by unit snapshots or visual inspection alone):** Inspect the *rendered* DOM and confirm: `aria-expanded` lands on the `<button>` (not the heading or panel) and matches current state; `aria-controls` value equals the panel's `id`; the panel `id` is unique across all items; collapsed panels carry `hidden`; the chevron carries `aria-hidden=\"true\"`; the button is wrapped in the configured heading level. Verify references *resolve* in the real output, not just in source.\n\n**Acceptance criteria (must all pass):**\n- \u2705 Each trigger is a native `<button type=\"button\">` wrapped in a configurable-level heading, inside a `<ul>`/`<li>` list.\n- \u2705 Each trigger has `aria-expanded` reflecting state and `aria-controls` pointing to its panel's unique `id`.\n- \u2705 Tab reaches every trigger; Enter and Space each toggle the associated panel.\n- \u2705 Collapsed panels are removed from tab order and AT tree (`hidden`/unmounted), not merely visually hidden.\n- \u2705 Focus stays on the trigger across toggles; focus indicator is visible (outline + box-shadow, `:focus-visible`) and unobscured.\n- \u2705 State change is announced by NVDA and VoiceOver; the chevron is not announced.\n- \u2705 State is signaled visually by more than color (panel visibility + chevron shape).\n- \u2705 axe-core passes on collapsed and expanded renders with zero violations; DOM verification confirms attribute placement.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Disclosure component (set + item) with ARIA wiring\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `Disclosure.tsx` (set wrapper), `DisclosureItem.tsx` (single item) or one component rendering the list; `Disclosure.module.css` (or design-system tokens); `Disclosure.test.tsx` (unit), `Disclosure.spec.ts` (Playwright keyboard).\n\n**Structure stub:**\n```\n<ul class=\"disclosure-set\">\n  <li class=\"disclosure-item\">\n    <h3 class=\"disclosure-heading\">         <!-- headingLevel prop -->\n      <button type=\"button\" id=\"disc-trigger-{n}\"\n              aria-expanded={isOpen}         <!-- \"true\" | \"false\" -->\n              aria-controls=\"disc-panel-{n}\">\n        <span class=\"disclosure-label\">{title}</span>\n        <span class=\"disclosure-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\" />\n      </button>\n    </h3>\n    <div id=\"disc-panel-{n}\" hidden={!isOpen}\n         /* role=\"region\" aria-labelledby=\"disc-trigger-{n}\" only if landmarkPanels */>\n      {children}\n    </div>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n```\n\n**ARIA attributes required:**\n- Trigger `aria-expanded` (true/false) \u2014 **WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value**\n- Trigger `aria-controls=\"<panelId>\"` \u2014 **WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships**\n- Icon `aria-hidden=\"true\"` \u2014 **WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content**, 4.1.2\n- (Conditional) Panel `role=\"region\"` + `aria-labelledby=\"<triggerId>\"` only for rich panels \u2014 **WCAG 1.3.1**\n- Unique `id` per trigger and panel (generate with React `useId`) \u2014 **WCAG 4.1.2** (references must resolve)\n\n**Keyboard interactions to implement:** None beyond a click/activate handler that flips state \u2014 native `<button>` supplies Tab focus and Enter/Space activation. Do **not** add `tabindex`, `role=\"button\"`, or a Space `keydown` `preventDefault`.\n\n**Focus management logic:** None special. Focus stays on the trigger; collapsed panel is `hidden` (or unmounted) so its contents leave the tab order. Provide `:focus-visible` styling (outline + box-shadow).\n\n**State communication logic:** One `isOpen` boolean per item drives BOTH `aria-expanded` and the panel's `hidden` \u2014 single source of truth, kept in sync.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Unit: renders N items; each trigger has matching `aria-controls`/panel `id`; `aria-expanded` starts `false`; toggling state flips `aria-expanded` and panel `hidden`; ids are unique.\n- Keyboard (Playwright, real events): Tab reaches triggers; Enter toggles; Space toggles; collapsed panel content not tabbable; expanded panel content tabbable.\n- DOM verification: attributes land on the correct elements; references resolve; chevron `aria-hidden`.\n\n**WCAG criteria satisfied:** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.11, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.6, 2.4.7, 2.5.8, 4.1.2.\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify APG Disclosure pattern is correctly applied (not Accordion); `aria-expanded` is on the `<button>` and toggles; `aria-controls` resolves to a unique panel `id`; trigger wrapped in a configurable heading inside a list; collapsed panels removed from tab order (not just `aria-hidden`); chevron hidden from AT; focus stays on trigger and the focus ring is visible/unobscured; no erroneous live region; state conveyed by more than color.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | APG Disclosure (not Accordion); `aria-expanded` on button + toggles; `aria-controls` resolves to unique panel id; heading-wrapped trigger in a list; collapsed panel out of tab order via `hidden`/unmount (not `aria-hidden` alone); chevron `aria-hidden`; visible/unobscured `:focus-visible` ring; no live region; non-color state cue; touch target \u226524px (target 44px) |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\nA reusable React **Disclosure** component: a `<ul>`/`<li>` list of items, each item a configurable-level heading wrapping a native `<button type=\"button\">` that toggles a sibling panel. ARIA is minimal and native-leaning: `aria-expanded` (state) + `aria-controls` (relationship) on the button; decorative chevron `aria-hidden`; collapsed panels hidden via the `hidden` attribute (or unmounted) so they leave the tab order and AT tree. No focus trap, no roving tabindex, no live region \u2014 chosen deliberately because panels open independently (Disclosure pattern, not Accordion). One `isOpen` boolean per item is the single source of truth driving both `aria-expanded` and panel visibility.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Disclosure component (set + item) with ARIA wiring\nEstimated Effort: **low** (single new component, well-documented APG pattern, native button does the heavy lifting; effort is in correct ARIA wiring, `:focus-visible` styling, and the keyboard/DOM test pass \u2014 no new files beyond one component + its CSS + two test files)\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\n- axe-core on collapsed AND expanded renders (duplicate ids, aria-controls resolution, valid ARIA, contrast, heading order).\n- Playwright real-key tests: Tab/Shift+Tab order, Enter toggles, Space toggles, collapsed panel content not tabbable, expanded panel content tabbable, focus stays on trigger, focus ring visible at 100/200/400% and unobscured.\n- NVDA+Firefox and VoiceOver+Safari: name+state+role on focus, state re-announced on activation, no chevron announcement, no double announcement.\n- DOM verification: `aria-expanded` on the button and matching state; `aria-controls` == panel `id`; ids unique; collapsed panels carry `hidden`; chevron `aria-hidden`; trigger wrapped in configured heading level.\n- Responsive/forced-colors/reduced-motion regression; touch target \u226524px (target 44px).\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\n- Native `<button type=\"button\">` per item, wrapped in a configurable-level heading, inside `<ul>`/`<li>`.\n- `aria-expanded` reflects state and toggles on Enter and Space; `aria-controls` resolves to a unique panel `id`.\n- Collapsed panels removed from tab order/AT tree (`hidden` or unmounted), not `aria-hidden` alone.\n- Focus stays on the trigger across toggles; `:focus-visible` ring (outline + box-shadow) visible and unobscured.\n- State announced by NVDA and VoiceOver; chevron not announced; state conveyed by more than color.\n- axe-core: zero violations on both states; DOM verification confirms attribute placement and reference resolution.\n\n### Failure Modes\n- **`aria-expanded` placed on the heading or panel instead of the button**, or not toggled in sync with visibility \u2192 state wrong/silent. (4.1.2)\n- **Collapsed panel hidden with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` or `visibility:hidden` while still focusable** \u2192 keyboard user Tabs into invisible content. Use `hidden`/`display:none`/unmount. (2.1.1, 2.4.3)\n- **Duplicate `id`s** across items (hardcoded ids on a reused component) \u2192 `aria-controls` points to the wrong panel. Use `useId`. (1.3.1, 4.1.2)\n- **Trigger built on a `<div>`** with `onClick` but no `role`/`tabindex`/key handling \u2192 not focusable, Space/Enter dead. Use native `<button>`. (2.1.1, 4.1.2)\n- **Chevron not hidden from AT** (text glyph announced as \"plus\"/\"triangle\") or **`aria-label`/`title` used as the accessible name** diverging from visible text \u2192 confusing/duplicated announcements, voice-control mismatch. (1.1.1, 2.5.3, 4.1.2)\n- **Hardcoded heading level** \u2192 heading-skip violation in some host pages. Make it a prop. (1.3.1, 2.4.6)\n- **Erroneous `aria-live`/`role=\"status\"`** on the widget \u2192 double announcement of state. Omit it; the focused control announces its own state.\n- **Missing/low-contrast or obscured focus indicator**, or `:focus` instead of `:focus-visible` showing the ring on mouse \u2192 keyboard users can't see focus / mouse users see noise. (2.4.7, 2.4.11)\n- **Tiny icon-only tap target** under 24px \u2192 fails AA target size on mobile. Make the whole row the button. (2.5.8)\n- **Adopting the Accordion pattern by mistake** (adding arrow-key navigation / roving tabindex) for independent toggles \u2192 unexpected interaction model and extra complexity. Keep Disclosure semantics.\n",
